    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-07T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-07T14:00:00-05:00" n="1"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">824.512/47: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Feely</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-07T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 7, 1932—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:19 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>75. The Chamber of Deputies in secret session yesterday passed, and the Senate
                    will undoubtedly approve, the 1 percent tax on capital, referred to in my
                    telegram 72, September 1, 4 p.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d1fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    the proceeds to be used for the national defense. Such a levy on foreign capital
                    invested in Bolivia would apparently be in violation of existing treaties, and
                    would directly affect Patiño Mines, Grace &amp; Company, Guggenheims, Bolivian
                    International Mining Corporation, and others.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Feely</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
